title: Homerton and Milltown
description: Flora and fauna in one of the 1' (minute) grids in the Victorian Biodiversity Atlas called E05. It is about 14 km long by 10 km wide and includes sections of the Darlot Creek, the Fitzroy River and Lake Condah, stony rises, heathy woodland, state forests and Mt Eccles National Park as well as roadside vegetation. The study started in about 2008 and is ongoing.

items.title: Dianella callicarpa
items.content_text: Growing in a damp area of sandy heath.

items.title: Hypericum humifusum
items.content_text: Note the small black dots on petals sepals and leaves, an identification feature.

items.title: Parentucellia viscosa
items.content_text: On a track in Annya SF. Now called Bellardia viscosa in Flora of Victoria.

items.title: Unidentified
items.content_text: A bracket fungus on fallen timber.

items.title: Amyema pendula
items.content_text: A set of four images. Growing on a melaleuca in a home garden but common in local bush nearby.

items.title: Polygonum plebeium
items.content_text:
Small sprawling herb growing in mud of drying ephemeral wetland.
Three images.

items.title: Alternanthera denticulata s.s.
items.content_text:
Three images.
Plants scrambling through reeds on the edge of a drying ephemeral swamp.

items.title: Lythrum hyssopifolia
items.content_text: Growing on the edge of a drying ephemeral wetland.

items.title: Atriplex prostrata
items.content_text:
Growing on edge of ephemeral swamp.
Two images.

items.title: Sigesbeckia orientalis subsp. orientalis
items.content_text: According to Flora Vic this is now just S. orientalis, and a native. This was growing on the edge of a drying swamp.

items.title: Rorippa palustris
items.content_text: Growing in drying ephemeral swamp. Identification suggested only.

items.title: Boronia nana var. nana
items.content_text: Late flowering record of this plant that grows in heathy woodland. Budj Bim NP . It normally flowers in spring.

items.title: Monotoca scoparia
items.content_text: Just starting to flower. Three images. Female flowers? Leaves distinctive.

items.title: Lepidosperma longitudinale
items.content_text: Three images showing male and female flowers a) anthers exerted and b) stigmas exerted. As well as the convex and twisted leaf.

items.title: Cycnogeton alcockiae
items.content_text: Triglochin possibly. It was growing in fresh water and the flower stalk was only about 15cm above water.

items.title: Gratiola spp.
items.content_text: Very small plants, growing in a damp spot. Possibly G. pubescens or G. peruviana.

items.title: Mentha pulegium
items.content_text: Small herb on the margin of Lake Condah.

items.title: Selliera radicans
items.content_text: Growing on the margin of Lake Condah on land exposed as water level receded over summer.

items.title: Potentilla anserina
items.content_text: Silverweed Argentina anserina has been recorded in Australia as Potentilla anserina, an alien species, but an article in Muelleria Vol 32 (2014) suggests it is an Australian species.

items.title: Sisyrinchium iridifolium
items.content_text: Sisyrinchium micranthum (Blue Pigroot), a weed on the roadside.

items.title: Xanthorrhoea minor subsp. lutea
items.content_text: Four images of the one plant.

items.title: Banksia marginata
items.content_text: In this area it can be prostrate in habit.

items.title: Drosera peltata s.l.
items.content_text: An insect trapped in the sticky leaf.
